# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: neural-simulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The **Blue Brain Project** was a Swiss brain research initiative that aimed to create a digital reconstruction of the mouse brain.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The project was founded in May 2005 by the Brain Mind Institute of *École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne* (EPFL) in Switzerland.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Its mission was to use biologically detailed digital reconstructions and simulations of the mammalian brain to identify the fundamental principles of brain structure and function.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The project was headed by the founding director Henry Markram—who also launched the European Human Brain Project—and was co-directed by Felix Schürmann, Adriana Salvatore and Sean Hill.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Using a Blue Gene supercomputer running Michael Hines's NEURON, the simulation involved a biologically realistic model of neurons and an empirically reconstructed model connectome.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] There were a number of collaborations, including the Cajal Blue Brain, which is coordinated by the Supercomputing and Visualization Center of Madrid (CeSViMa), and others run by universities and independent laboratories.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] In 2006, the project made its first model of a neocortical column with simplified neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] In November 2007, it completed an initial model of the rat neocortical column.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] This marked the end of the first phase, delivering a data-driven process for creating, validating, and researching the neocortical column.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Neocortical columns are considered by some researchers to be the smallest functional units of the neocortex, and they are thought to be responsible for higher functions such as conscious thought.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] In humans, each column is about 2 mm (0.079 in) in length, has a diameter of 0.5 mm (0.020 in) and contains about 60,000 neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Rat neocortical columns are very similar in structure but contain only 10,000 neurons and 108 synapses.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] In 2009, Henry Markram claimed that a "detailed, functional artificial human brain can be built within the next 10 years".
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] He conceived the Human Brain Project, to which the Blue Brain Project contributed, and which became funded in 2013 by the European Union with up to $1.3 billion.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] In 2015, the project simulated part of a rat brain with 30,000 neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Also in 2015, scientists at École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) developed a quantitative model of the previously unknown relationship between the neurons and the astrocytes.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] This model describes the energy management of the brain through the function of the neuro-glial vascular unit (NGV).
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The additional layer of neuron and glial cells is being added to Blue Brain Project models to improve functionality of the system.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] In 2017, Blue Brain Project discovered that neural cliques connected to one another in up to eleven dimensions.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The project's director suggested that the difficulty of understanding the brain is partly because the mathematics usually applied for studying neural networks cannot detect that many dimensions.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The Blue Brain Project was able to model these networks using algebraic topology.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] In 2018, Blue Brain Project released its first digital 3D brain cell atlas which, according to *ScienceDaily*, is like "going from hand-drawn maps to Google Earth", providing information about major cell types, numbers, and positions in 737 regions of the brain.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] He also mentioned that the model had become too heavy on the supercomputers they were using at the time, and that they were consequently exploring methods in which every neuron could be represented as an artificial neural network.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] In 2022, scientists at the Blue Brain Project used algebraic topology to create an algorithm, Topological Neuronal Synthesis, that generates a large number of unique cells using only a few examples, synthesizing millions of unique neuronal morphologies.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] This allows them to replicate both healthy and diseased states of the brain.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] In a paper Kenari et al. were able to digitally synthesize dendritic morphologies from the mouse brain using this algorithm.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] They mapped entire brain regions from just a few reference cells.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Since it is open source, this will enable the modelling of brain diseases and eventually, the algorithm could lead to digital twins of brains.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The Blue Brain Project has developed a number of software to reconstruct and to simulate the mouse brain.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] All software tools mentioned below are open source software and available for everyone on GitHub.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Blue Brain Nexus is a data integration platform which uses a knowledge graph to enable users to search, deposit, and organise data.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] It stands on the FAIR data principles to provide flexible data management solutions beyond neuroscience studies.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] BluePyOpt is a tool that is used to build electrical models of single neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] For this, it uses evolutionary algorithms to constrain the parameters to experimental electrophysiological data.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Attempts to reconstruct single neurons using BluePyOpt are reported by Rosanna Migliore, and Stefano Masori.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] CoreNEURON is a supplemental tool to NEURON, which allows large scale simulation by boosting memory usage and computational speed.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] NeuroMorphoVis is a visualisation tool for morphologies of neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] SONATA is a joint effort between Blue Brain Project and Allen Institute for Brain Science, to develop a standard for data format, which realises a multiple platform working environment with greater computational memory and efficiency.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The project was funded primarily by the Swiss government and the Future and Emerging Technologies (FET) Flagship grant from the European Commission, and secondarily by grants and donations from private individuals.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The EPFL bought the Blue Gene computer at a reduced cost because it was still a prototype and IBM was interested in exploring how applications would perform on the machine.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] BBP was viewed as a validation of the Blue Gene supercomputer concept.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The Cajal Blue Brain Project is coordinated by the Technical University of Madrid led by Javier de Felipe and uses the facilities of the Supercomputing and Visualization Center of Madrid and its supercomputer Magerit.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The Cajal Institute also participates in this collaboration.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The main lines of research currently being pursued at Cajal Blue Brain include neurological experimentation and computer simulations.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Nanotechnology, in the form of a newly designed brain microscope, plays an important role in its research plans.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] Noah Hutton created the documentary film *In Silico* over a 10-year period.
[src:neural-simulation/blue-brain-project] The film covers the "shifting goals and landmarks" of the Blue Brain Project as well as the drama, "In the end, this isn't about science.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] Brian is aimed at researchers developing models based on networks of spiking neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] The general design is aimed at maximising flexibility, simplicity and users' development speed.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] Users specify neuron models by giving their differential equations in standard mathematical form as strings, create groups of neurons and connect them via synapses.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] This is in contrast to the approach taken by many neural simulators in which users select from a predefined set of neuron models.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] Computationally, it is based around the concept of code generation: users specify the model in Python but behind the scenes Brian generates, compiles and runs code in one of several languages (including Python, Cython and C++).
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] In addition there is a "standalone" mode in which Brian generates an entire C++ source code tree with no dependency on Brian, allowing models to be run on platforms where Python is not available.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] The following code defines, runs and plots a randomly connected network of leaky integrate and fire neurons with exponential inhibitory and excitatory currents.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] Brian is primarily, although not solely, aimed at single compartment neuron models.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] Simulators focused on multi-compartmental models include Neuron, GENESIS, and its derivatives.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] The focus of Brian is on flexibility and ease of use, and only supports simulations running on a single machine.
[src:neural-simulation/brian-software] The NEST simulator includes facilities for distributing simulations across a cluster.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] Compartmental modelling is a very natural way of modelling dynamical systems that have certain inherent properties with conservation principles.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] The compartmental modelling is an elegant way, a state space formulation to elegantly capture the dynamical systems that are governed by the conservation laws.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] Whether it is the conservation of mass, energy, fluid flow or information flow.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] Basically, they are models whose state variables tend to be non-negative (such as mass, concentrations, energy).
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] So the equations for mass balance, energy, concentration or fluid flow can be written.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] It ultimately goes down to networks in which the brain is the largest of them all, just like Avogadro number, very large amount of molecules that are interconnected.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] The brain has very interesting interconnections.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] On a microscopic level thermodynamics is virtually impossible to understand but from a macroscopic view we see that these follow some universal laws.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] In the same way brain has numerous interconnections, which is almost impossible to write a differential equation for.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] General observations about how the brain functions can be made by looking at the first and second thermodynamic laws, which are universal laws.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] Brain is a very large-scale interconnected system; the neurons have to somehow behave like the chemical reaction system, so, it has to somehow obey the chemical thermodynamic laws.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] This approach may lead to more generalized model of brain.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] are obtained by inverting eq(3) and dividing by surface area of interest.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] is the surface area of the compartment i.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] For increment in the potential, coupled system current should be greater than that is required for uncoupled system.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] This is because the second compartment drains some current.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] Each dendritic section is subdivided into segments, which are typically seen as uniform circular cylinders or tapered circular cylinders.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] In the traditional compartmental model, point process location is determined only to an accuracy of half segment length.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] This will make the model solution particularly sensitive to segment boundaries.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] The accuracy of the traditional approach for this reason is O(1/n) when a point current and synaptic input is present.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] Usually the trans-membrane current where the membrane potential is known is represented in the model at points, or nodes and is assumed to be at the center.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] The new approach partitions the effect of the input by distributing it to the boundaries of the segment.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] Hence any input is partitioned between the nodes at the proximal and distal boundaries of the segment.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] Therefore, this procedure makes sure that the solution obtained is not sensitive to small changes in location of these boundaries because it affects how the input is partitioned between the nodes.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] When these compartments are connected with continuous potentials and conservation of current at segment boundaries then a new compartmental model of a new mathematical form is obtained.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] This new approach also provides a model identical to the traditional model but an order more accurate.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] This model increases the accuracy and precision by an order of magnitude than that is achieved by point process input.
[src:neural-simulation/compartmental-modelling-of-dendrites] Dendrites and axons are considered to be continuous (cable-like), rather than series of compartments.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] GENESIS works by creating simulation environments for constructing models of neurons or neural systems.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] "Nerve cells are capable of communicating with each other in such a highly structured manner as to form neuronal networks.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] To understand neural networks, it is necessary to understand the ways in which one neuron communicates with another through synaptic connections and the process called synaptic transmission".
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Neurons have a specialized structure for their function, they "are different from most other cells in the body in that they are polarized and have distinct morphological regions, each with specific functions".
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] The two important regions of a neuron are the dendrite and the axon.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] "Dendrites are the region where one neuron receives connections from other neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] The cell body or soma contains the nucleus and the other organelles necessary for cellular function.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] The axon is a key component of nerve cells over which information is transmitted from one part of the neuron (e.g., the cell body) to the terminal regions of the neuron".
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] The third important piece of a neuron is the synapse.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] "The synapse is the terminal region of the axon this is where one neuron forms a connection with another and conveys information through the process of synaptic transmission".
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Neural networks like the ones simulated with GENESIS software can quickly become highly complex and difficult to understand.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] "Just a few interconnected neurons (a microcircuit) can perform sophisticated tasks such as mediate reflexes, process sensory information, generate locomotion and mediate learning and memory.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Even more complex networks, macrocircuits, consist of multiple embedded microcircuits.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Macrocircuits mediate higher brain functions such as object recognition and cognition".
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] GENESIS endeavors to simulate neural systems as they are found in nature.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Often, "a neuron can receive contacts from up to 10,000 presynaptic neurons, and, in turn, any one neuron can contact up to 10,000 postsynaptic neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] The combinatorial possibility could give rise to enormously complex neuronal circuits or network topologies, which might be very difficult to understand".
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Bower, in the Caltech laboratory, and first released to the public in 1988 in association with the first Methods in Computational Neuroscience Course at the Marine Biological Laboratory in Woods Hole, MA.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Full source code for the software was released in the same year under an open software model for development.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] It's now supported by the Computational Biology Initiative at the University of Texas at San Antonio and is available free along with tutorial guides on its use.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] P-GENESIS, a parallel version of GENESIS, was first run in 1990 on the Intel Delta, which was the prototype for the Intel Paragon family of massively parallel supercomputers.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] The GENESIS system is complicated, but relatively easy to use.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] An individual can input commands through one of three ways: script files, graphical user interface, or the GENESIS command shell.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] These commands are then processed by the script language interpreter.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] "The Script Language Interpreter processes commands entered through the keyboard, script files, or the graphical user interface, and passes them to the GENESIS simulation engine.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] The simulation engine also loads compiled object libraries, reads and writes data files, and interacts with the graphical user interface".
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Below is a graphical representation of the user input process and a sample GENESIS output.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Most current applications for GENESIS involve realistic simulations of biological systems.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] It is usually used to simulate the behavior of larger brain structures, for example the cerebral cortex.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] These studies most often occur in lab courses in neural simulation at Caltech and the Marine Biological Laboratory at Woods Hole, Massachusetts.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] GENESIS can be used in combination with Yale University’s software called NEURON as a means for scientists to collaborate to construct a physical description of the nervous system.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] The GENESIS software can also be used with Kinetikit in the modeling of signal transduction pathways.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Some of these studies involve research that focuses on the development of software that would be useful across many disciplines.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Others are studies of neurons, such as Purkinje cells.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] These studies used GENESIS to simulate Purkinje cells and could be useful for the planning and development of later experiments using the GENESIS software.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] There may also be biomedical applications of the software.
[src:neural-simulation/genesis-software] Jude Medical in Europe has developed an implanted GENESIS device.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Central to these models is the description of how the membrane potential (that is, the difference in electric potential between the interior and the exterior of a biological cell) across the cell membrane changes over time.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In an experimental setting, stimulating neurons with an electrical current generates an action potential (or spike), that propagates down the neuron's axon.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This axon can branch out and connect to a large number of downstream neurons at sites called synapses.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] At these synapses, the spike can cause the release of neurotransmitters, which in turn can change the voltage potential of downstream neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This change can potentially lead to even more spikes in those downstream neurons, thus passing down the signal.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] As many as 95% of neurons in the neocortex, the outermost layer of the mammalian brain, consist of excitatory pyramidal neurons, and each pyramidal neuron receives tens of thousands of inputs from other neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Thus, spiking neurons are a major information processing unit of the nervous system.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] One such example of a spiking neuron model may be a highly detailed mathematical model that includes spatial morphology.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Another may be a conductance-based neuron model that views neurons as points and describes the membrane voltage dynamics as a function of trans-membrane currents.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] A mathematically simpler "integrate-and-fire" model significantly simplifies the description of ion channel and membrane potential dynamics (initially studied by Lapique in 1907).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Not all the cells of the nervous system produce the type of spike that defines the scope of the spiking neuron models.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For example, cochlear hair cells, retinal receptor cells, and retinal bipolar cells do not spike.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Furthermore, many cells in the nervous system are not classified as neurons but instead are classified as glia.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Neuronal activity can be measured with different experimental techniques, such as the "Whole cell" measurement technique, which captures the spiking activity of a single neuron and produces full amplitude action potentials.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] With extracellular measurement techniques, one or more electrodes are placed in the extracellular space.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Spikes, often from several spiking sources, depending on the size of the electrode and its proximity to the sources, can be identified with signal processing techniques.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Neuron models can be divided into two categories according to the physical units of the interface of the model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Natural stimulus or pharmacological input neuron models – The models in this category connect the input stimulus, which can be either pharmacological or natural, to the probability of a spike event.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The input stage of these models is not electrical but rather has either pharmacological (chemical) concentration units, or physical units that characterize an external stimulus such as light, sound, or other forms of physical pressure.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Furthermore, the output stage represents the probability of a spike event and not an electrical voltage.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Although it is not unusual in science and engineering to have several descriptive models for different abstraction/detail levels, the number of different, sometimes contradicting, biological neuron models is exceptionally high.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This situation is partly the result of the many different experimental settings, and the difficulty to separate the intrinsic properties of a single neuron from measurement effects and interactions of many cells (network effects).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Ultimately, biological neuron models aim to explain the mechanisms underlying the operation of the nervous system.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] However, several approaches can be distinguished, from more realistic models (e.g., mechanistic models) to more pragmatic models (e.g., phenomenological models).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Modeling helps to analyze experimental data and address questions.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Models are also important in the context of restoring lost brain functionality through neuroprosthetic devices.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The models in this category describe the relationship between neuronal membrane currents at the input stage and membrane voltage at the output stage.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This category includes (generalized) integrate-and-fire models and biophysical models inspired by the work of Hodgkin–Huxley in the early 1950s using an experimental setup that punctured the cell membrane and allowed to force a specific membrane voltage/current.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Most modern electrical neural interfaces apply extra-cellular electrical stimulation to avoid membrane puncturing, which can lead to cell death and tissue damage.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Hence, it is not clear to what extent the electrical neuron models hold for extra-cellular stimulation (see e.g.).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The Hodgkin–Huxley model (H&H model) is a model of the relationship between the flow of ionic currents across the neuronal cell membrane and the membrane voltage of the cell.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] It consists of a set of nonlinear differential equations describing the behavior of ion channels that permeate the cell membrane of the squid giant axon.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Hodgkin and Huxley were awarded the 1963 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for this work.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The above equation is the time derivative of the law of capacitance, *Q* = *CV* where the change of the total charge must be explained as the sum over the currents.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where *g*(*t*,*V*) is the conductance, or inverse resistance, which can be expanded in terms of its maximal conductance *ḡ* and the activation and inactivation fractions *m* and *h*, respectively, that determine how many ions can flow through available membrane channels.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] with similar dynamics for *h*, where we can use either *τ* and *m*∞ or *α* and *β* to define our gate fractions.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The Hodgkin–Huxley model may be extended to include additional ionic currents.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Typically, these include inward Ca2+ and Na+ input currents, as well as several varieties of K+ outward currents, including a "leak" current.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The result can be at the small end of 20 parameters which one must estimate or measure for an accurate model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In a model of a complex system of neurons, numerical integration of the equations are computationally expensive.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Careful simplifications of the Hodgkin–Huxley model are therefore needed.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The model can be reduced to two dimensions thanks to the dynamic relations which can be established between the gating variables. it is also possible to extend it to take into account the evolution of the concentrations (considered fixed in the original model).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] One of the earliest models of a neuron is the perfect integrate-and-fire model (also called non-leaky integrate-and-fire), first investigated in 1907 by Louis Lapicque.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] which is just the time derivative of the law of capacitance, *Q* = *CV*.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] When an input current is applied, the membrane voltage increases with time until it reaches a constant threshold *V*th, at which point a delta function spike occurs and the voltage is reset to its resting potential, after which the model continues to run.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The *firing frequency* of the model thus increases linearly without bound as input current increases.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The model can be made more accurate by introducing a refractory period *t*ref that limits the firing frequency of a neuron by preventing it from firing during that period.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For constant input *I(t)=I* the threshold voltage is reached after an integration time tint=CVthr/I after starting from zero.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] After a reset, the refractory period introduces a dead time so that the total time until the next firing is *t*ref+*t*int .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The firing frequency is the inverse of the total inter-spike interval (including dead time).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] A shortcoming of this model is that it describes neither adaptation nor leakage.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] If the model receives a below-threshold short current pulse at some time, it will retain that voltage boost forever - until another input later makes it fire.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This characteristic is not in line with observed neuronal behavior.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The following extensions make the integrate-and-fire model more plausible from a biological point of view.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The leaky integrate-and-fire model, which can be traced back to Louis Lapicque, contains a "leak" term in the membrane potential equation that reflects the diffusion of ions through the membrane, unlike the non-leaky integrate-and-fire model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where *V*m is the voltage across the cell membrane and *R*m is the membrane resistance.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] (The non-leaky integrate-and-fire model is retrieved in the limit *R*m to infinity, i.e. if the membrane is a perfect insulator).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The model equation is valid for arbitrary time-dependent input until a threshold *V*th is reached; thereafter the membrane potential is reset.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For constant input, the minimum input to reach the threshold is *I*th = *V*th / *R*m.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] which converges for large input currents to the previous leak-free model with the refractory period.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The model can also be used for inhibitory neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The most significant disadvantage of this model is that it does not contain neuronal adaptation, so that it cannot describe an experimentally measured spike train in response to constant input current.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This disadvantage is removed in generalized integrate-and-fire models that also contain one or several adaptation-variables and are able to predict spike times of cortical neurons under current injection to a high degree of accuracy.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Neuronal adaptation refers to the fact that even in the presence of a constant current injection into the soma, the intervals between output spikes increase.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where $\tau _{m}$ is the membrane time constant, *w*k is the adaptation current number, with index *k*, $\tau _{k}$ is the time constant of adaptation current *w**k*, *E*m is the resting potential and *t*f is the firing time of the neuron and the Greek delta denotes the Dirac delta function.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Whenever the voltage reaches the firing threshold the voltage is reset to a value *V*r below the firing threshold.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The reset value is one of the important parameters of the model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The simplest model of adaptation has only a single adaptation variable *w* and the sum over k is removed.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Integrate-and-fire neurons with one or several adaptation variables can account for a variety of neuronal firing patterns in response to constant stimulation, including adaptation, bursting, and initial bursting.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Moreover, adaptive integrate-and-fire neurons with several adaptation variables are able to predict spike times of cortical neurons under time-dependent current injection into the soma.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Recent advances in computational and theoretical fractional calculus lead to a new form of model called Fractional-order leaky integrate-and-fire.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] An advantage of this model is that it can capture adaptation effects with a single variable.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Once the voltage hits the threshold it is reset.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Fractional integration has been used to account for neuronal adaptation in experimental data.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where V is the membrane potential, $V_{T}$ is the intrinsic membrane potential threshold, $\tau _{m}$ is the membrane time constant, $E_{m}$ is the resting potential, and $\Delta _{T}$ is the sharpness of action potential initiation, usually around 1 mV for cortical pyramidal neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Once the membrane potential crosses $V_{T}$ , it diverges to infinity in finite time.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In numerical simulation the integration is stopped if the membrane potential hits an arbitrary threshold (much larger than $V_{T}$ ) at which the membrane potential is reset to a value *V*r .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The voltage reset value *V*r is one of the important parameters of the model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Importantly, the right-hand side of the above equation contains a nonlinearity that can be directly extracted from experimental data.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In this sense the exponential nonlinearity is strongly supported by experimental evidence.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where *w* denotes the adaptation current with time scale $\tau$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Important model parameters are the voltage reset value *V*r, the intrinsic threshold $V_{T}$ , the time constants $\tau$ and $\tau _{m}$ as well as the coupling parameters *a* and *b*.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The adaptive exponential integrate-and-fire model inherits the experimentally derived voltage nonlinearity of the exponential integrate-and-fire model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] But going beyond this model, it can also account for a variety of neuronal firing patterns in response to constant stimulation, including adaptation, bursting, and initial bursting.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] However, since the adaptation is in the form of a current, aberrant hyperpolarization may appear.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This problem was solved by expressing it as a conductance.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In this model, a time-dependent function $\theta (t)$ is added to the fixed threshold, $v_{th0}$ , after every spike, causing an adaptation of the threshold.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The threshold potential, $v_{th}$ , gradually returns to its steady state value depending on the threshold adaptation time constant $\tau _{\theta }$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This is one of the simpler techniques to achieve spike frequency adaptation.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] A simpler version of this with a single time constant in threshold decay with an LIF neuron is realized in to achieve LSTM like recurrent spiking neural networks to achieve accuracy nearer to ANNs on few spatio temporal tasks.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The DEXAT neuron model is a flavor of adaptive neuron model in which the threshold voltage decays with a double exponential having two time constants.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Double exponential decay is governed by a fast initial decay and then a slower decay over a longer period of time.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This neuron used in SNNs through surrogate gradient creates an adaptive learning rate yielding higher accuracy and faster convergence, and flexible long short-term memory compared to existing counterparts in the literature.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Further, multi-time scale adaptive threshold neuron model showing more complex dynamics is shown in.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The models in this category are generalized integrate-and-fire models that include a certain level of stochasticity.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Cortical neurons in experiments are found to respond reliably to time-dependent input, albeit with a small degree of variations between one trial and the next if the same stimulus is repeated.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Stochasticity in neurons has two important sources.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] First, even in a very controlled experiment where input current is injected directly into the soma, ion channels open and close stochastically and this channel noise leads to a small amount of variability in the exact value of the membrane potential and the exact timing of output spikes.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Second, for a neuron embedded in a cortical network, it is hard to control the exact input because most inputs come from unobserved neurons somewhere else in the brain.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The relation of noise in neuron models to the variability of spike trains and neural codes is discussed in Neural Coding and in Chapter 7 of the textbook Neuronal Dynamics.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] A neuron embedded in a network receives spike input from other neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Since the spike arrival times are not controlled by an experimentalist they can be considered as stochastic.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Thus a (potentially nonlinear) integrate-and-fire model with nonlinearity f(v) receives two inputs: an input $I(t)$ controlled by the experimentalists and a noisy input current $I^{\rm {noise}}(t)$ that describes the uncontrolled background input.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] However, in contrast to the standard Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process, the membrane voltage is reset whenever *V* hits the firing threshold *V*th .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Calculating the interval distribution of the Ornstein–Uhlenbeck model for constant input with threshold leads to a first-passage time problem.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Stein's neuron model and variants thereof have been used to fit interspike interval distributions of spike trains from real neurons under constant input current.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where $\sigma$ is the amplitude of the noise input and *dW* are increments of a Wiener process.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where y is drawn from a Gaussian distribution with zero mean unit variance.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The voltage is reset when it hits the firing threshold *V*th .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The noisy input model can also be used in generalized integrate-and-fire models.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For constant deterministic input $I(t)=I_{0}$ it is possible to calculate the mean firing rate as a function of $I_{0}$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This is important because the frequency-current relation (f-I-curve) is often used by experimentalists to characterize a neuron.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The leaky integrate-and-fire with noisy input has been widely used in the analysis of networks of spiking neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Noisy input is also called 'diffusive noise' because it leads to a diffusion of the subthreshold membrane potential around the noise-free trajectory (Johannesma, The theory of spiking neurons with noisy input is reviewed in Chapter 8.2 of the textbook *Neuronal Dynamics*.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In deterministic integrate-and-fire models, a spike is generated if the membrane potential *V*(t) hits the threshold $V_{th}$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In noisy output models, the strict threshold is replaced by a noisy one as follows.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] that depends on the momentary difference between the membrane voltage *V*(t) and the threshold $V_{th}$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where $\tau _{0}$ is a time constant that describes how quickly a spike is fired once the membrane potential reaches the threshold and $\beta$ is a sharpness parameter.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For $\beta \to \infty$ the threshold becomes sharp and spike firing occurs deterministically at the moment when the membrane potential hits the threshold from below.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The sharpness value found in experiments is $1/\beta \approx 4mV$ which means that neuronal firing becomes non-negligible as soon as the membrane potential is a few mV below the formal firing threshold.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] that depends on the momentary difference between the membrane voltage *V* at time $t_{n}$ and the threshold $V_{th}$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The function F is often taken as a standard sigmoidal $F(x)=0.5[1+\tanh(\gamma x)]$ with steepness parameter $\gamma$ , similar to the update dynamics in artificial neural networks.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] But the functional form of F can also be derived from the stochastic intensity f in continuous time introduced above as $F(y_{n})\approx 1-\exp[y_{n}\Delta t]$ where $y_{n}=V(t_{n})-V_{th}$ is the threshold distance.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Integrate-and-fire models with output noise can be used to predict the peristimulus time histogram (PSTH) of real neurons under arbitrary time-dependent input.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For non-adaptive integrate-and-fire neurons, the interval distribution under constant stimulation can be calculated from stationary renewal theory.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The spike response model (SRM) is a generalized linear model for the subthreshold membrane voltage combined with a nonlinear output noise process for spike generation.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The contributions to the voltage caused by a spike at time $t^{f}$ are described by the refractory kernel $\eta (t-t^{f})$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In particular, $\eta (t-t^{f})$ describes the reset after the spike and the time course of the spike-afterpotential following a spike.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] It therefore expresses the consequences of refractoriness and adaptation.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The voltage V(t) can be interpreted as the result of an integration of the differential equation of a leaky integrate-and-fire model coupled to an arbitrary number of spike-triggered adaptation variables.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Here $\vartheta _{0}$ is the firing threshold of an inactive neuron and $\theta _{1}(t-t^{f})$ describes the increase of the threshold after a spike at time $t^{f}$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In case of a fixed threshold, one sets $\theta _{1}(t-t^{f})=0$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For $\beta \to \infty$ the threshold process is deterministic.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The time course of the filters $\eta ,\kappa ,\theta _{1}$ that characterize the spike response model can be directly extracted from experimental data.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] With optimized parameters the SRM describes the time course of the subthreshold membrane voltage for time-dependent input with a precision of 2mV and can predict the timing of most output spikes with a precision of 4ms.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The SRM is closely related to linear-nonlinear-Poisson cascade models (also called Generalized Linear Model).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The estimation of parameters of probabilistic neuron models such as the SRM using methods developed for Generalized Linear Models is discussed in Chapter 10 of the textbook *Neuronal Dynamics*.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The time course $\varepsilon _{ij}(s)$ of the PSP results from the convolution of the postsynaptic current $I(t)$ caused by the arrival of a presynaptic spike from neuron j with the membrane filter $\kappa (s)$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The **SRM0** is a stochastic neuron model related to time-dependent nonlinear renewal theory and a simplification of the Spike Response Model (SRM).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The main difference to the voltage equation of the SRM introduced above is that in the term containing the refractory kernel $\eta (s)$ there is no summation sign over past spikes: only the *most recent spike* (denoted as the time ${\hat {t}}$ ) matters.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Another difference is that the threshold is constant.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The model SRM0 can be formulated in discrete or continuous time.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where ${\hat {t}}_{i}$ is the *last firing time neuron* i.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Note that the time course of the postsynaptic potential $\varepsilon _{ij}$ is also allowed to depend on the time since the last spike of neuron i to describe a change in membrane conductance during refractoriness.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where $V_{th}$ is a fixed firing threshold.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Thus spike firing of neuron i depends only on its input and the time since neuron i has fired its last spike.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] With the SRM0, the interspike-interval distribution for constant input can be mathematically linked to the shape of the refractory kernel $\eta$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Moreover the stationary frequency-current relation can be calculated from the escape rate in combination with the refractory kernel $\eta$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] With an appropriate choice of the kernels, the SRM0 approximates the dynamics of the Hodgkin-Huxley model to a high degree of accuracy.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Moreover, the PSTH response to arbitrary time-dependent input can be predicted.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The models in this category are highly simplified toy models that qualitatively describe the membrane voltage as a function of input.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] They are mainly used for didactic reasons in teaching but are not considered valid neuron models for large-scale simulations or data fitting.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Sweeping simplifications to Hodgkin–Huxley were introduced by FitzHugh and Nagumo in 1961 and 1962.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where we again have a membrane-like voltage and input current with a slower general gate voltage *w* and experimentally-determined parameters *a* = -0.7, *b* = 0.8, *τ* = 1/0.08.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Although not derivable from biology, the model allows for a simplified, immediately available dynamic, without being a trivial simplification.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The experimental support is weak, but the model is useful as a didactic tool to introduce dynamics of spike generation through phase plane analysis.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] See Chapter 7 in the textbook *Methods of Neuronal Modeling*.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The experimental support of the model is weak, but the model is useful as a didactic tool to introduce dynamics of spike generation through phase plane analysis.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] A two-dimensional neuron model very similar to the Morris-Lecar model can be derived step-by-step starting from the Hodgkin-Huxley model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] See Chapter 4.2 in the textbook Neuronal Dynamics.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] with *r*2 = *x*2 + *y*2 + *z*2, and *r* ≈ 10−2 so that the *z* variable only changes very slowly.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This extra mathematical complexity allows a great variety of dynamic behaviors for the membrane potential, described by the *x* variable of the model, which includes chaotic dynamics.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] This makes the Hindmarsh–Rose neuron model very useful, because it is still simple, allows a good qualitative description of the many different firing patterns of the action potential, in particular bursting, observed in experiments.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Nevertheless, it remains a toy model and has not been fitted to experimental data.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] It is widely used as a reference model for bursting dynamics.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The theta model, or Ermentrout–Kopell canonical Type I model, is mathematically equivalent to the quadratic integrate-and-fire model which in turn is an approximation to the exponential integrate-and-fire model and the Hodgkin-Huxley model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] It is called a canonical model because it is one of the generic models for constant input close to the bifurcation point, which means close to the transition from silent to repetitive firing.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The equivalence of theta model and quadratic integrate-and-fire is for example reviewed in Chapter 4.1.2.2 of spiking neuron models.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The models in this category were derived following experiments involving natural stimulation such as light, sound, touch, or odor.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In these experiments, the spike pattern resulting from each stimulus presentation varies from trial to trial, but the averaged response from several trials often converges to a clear pattern.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Consequently, the models in this category generate a probabilistic relationship between the input stimulus to spike occurrences.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Siebert modeled the neuron spike firing pattern using a non-homogeneous Poisson process model, following experiments involving the auditory system.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Siebert considered several functions as $g[s(t)]$ , including $g[s(t)]\propto s^{2}(t)$ for low stimulus intensities.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The main advantage of Siebert's model is its simplicity.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] These shortcomings are addressed by the age-dependent point process model and the two-state Markov Model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The model is also called an *inhomogeneous Markov interval (IMI) process*.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Similar models have been used for many years in auditory neuroscience.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Since the model keeps memory of the last spike time it is non-Poisson and falls in the class of time-dependent renewal models.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] It is closely related to the model SRM0 with exponential escape rate.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Importantly, it is possible to fit parameters of the age-dependent point process model so as to describe not just the PSTH response, but also the interspike-interval statistics.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The linear-nonlinear-Poisson cascade model is a cascade of a linear filtering process followed by a nonlinear spike generation step.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] In the case that output spikes feed back, via a linear filtering process, we arrive at a model that is known in the neurosciences as Generalized Linear Model (GLM).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The spiking neuron model by Nossenson & Messer produces the probability of the neuron firing a spike as a function of either an external or pharmacological stimulus.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The model consists of a cascade of a receptor layer model and a spiking neuron model, as shown in Fig 4.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Thus, the spiking neuron model by itself depends on neurotransmitter concentration at the input stage.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] An important feature of this model is the prediction for neurons firing rate pattern which captures, using a low number of free parameters, the characteristic edge emphasized response of neurons to a stimulus pulse, as shown in Fig.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The firing rate is identified both as a normalized probability for neural spike firing and as a quantity proportional to the current of neurotransmitters released by the cell.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] P0 could be generally calculated recursively using the Euler method, but in the case of a pulse of stimulus, it yields a simple closed-form expression.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] with $\langle s^{2}(t)\rangle$ being a short temporal average of stimulus power (given in Watt or other energy per time unit).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] 1) The averaged evoked response potential (ERP) due to the population of many neurons in unfiltered measurements resembles the firing rate.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] 2) The voltage variance of activity due to multiple neuron activity resembles the firing rate (also known as Multi-Unit-Activity power or MUA).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] 3) The inter-spike-interval probability distribution takes the form a gamma-distribution like function.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The models in this category produce predictions for experiments involving pharmacological stimulation.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] According to the model by Koch and Segev, the response of a neuron to individual neurotransmitters can be modeled as an extension of the classical Hodgkin–Huxley model with both standard and nonstandard kinetic currents.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Four neurotransmitters primarily influence the CNS.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] AMPA/kainate receptors are fast excitatory mediators while NMDA receptors mediate considerably slower currents.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] Fast inhibitory currents go through GABAA receptors, while GABAB receptors mediate by secondary *G*-protein-activated potassium channels.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] where *ḡ* is the maximal conductance (around 1S) and *E* is the equilibrium potential of the given ion or transmitter (AMDA, NMDA, Cl, or K), while [*O*] describes the fraction of open receptors.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For NMDA, there is a significant effect of *magnesium block* that depends sigmoidally on the concentration of intracellular magnesium by *B*(*V*).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For GABAB, [*G*] is the concentration of the *G*-protein, and *K*d describes the dissociation of *G* in binding to the potassium gates.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The dynamics of this more complicated model have been well-studied experimentally and produce important results in terms of very quick synaptic potentiation and depression, that is fast, short-term learning.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The stochastic **model by Nossenson and Messer** translates neurotransmitter concentration at the input stage to the probability of releasing neurotransmitter at the output stage.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] For a more detailed description of this model, see the Two state Markov model section above.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] The HTM neuron model was developed by Jeff Hawkins and researchers at Numenta and is based on a theory called Hierarchical Temporal Memory, originally described in the book *On Intelligence*.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p01] It is based on neuroscience and the physiology and interaction of pyramidal neurons in the neocortex of the human brain.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Spiking Neuron Models are used in a variety of applications that need encoding into or decoding from neuronal spike trains in the context of neuroprosthesis and brain-computer interfaces such as retinal prosthesis: or artificial limb control and sensation.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Applications are not part of this article; for more information on this topic please refer to the main article.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The most basic model of a neuron consists of an input with some synaptic weight vector and an activation function or transfer function inside the neuron determining output.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] where *y**i* is the output of the *i* th neuron, *x**j* is the *j*th input neuron signal, *w**ij* is the synaptic weight (or strength of connection) between the neurons *i* and *j*, and *φ* is the activation function.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] While this model has seen success in machine-learning applications, it is a poor model for real (biological) neurons, because it lacks time-dependence in input and output.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] When an input is switched on at a time t and kept constant thereafter, biological neurons emit a spike train.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Importantly, this spike train is not regular but exhibits a temporal structure characterized by adaptation, bursting, or initial bursting followed by regular spiking.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Generalized integrate-and-fire models such as the Adaptive Exponential Integrate-and-Fire model, the spike response model, or the (linear) adaptive integrate-and-fire model can capture these neuronal firing patterns.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Moreover, neuronal input in the brain is time-dependent.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Time-dependent input is transformed by complex linear and nonlinear filters into a spike train in the output.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Again, the spike response model or the adaptive integrate-and-fire model enables to prediction of the spike train in the output for arbitrary time-dependent input, whereas an artificial neuron or a simple leaky integrate-and-fire does not.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] If we take the Hodkgin-Huxley model as a starting point, generalized integrate-and-fire models can be derived systematically in a step-by-step simplification procedure.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] This has been shown explicitly for the exponential integrate-and-fire model and the spike response model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] In the case of modeling a biological neuron, physical analogs are used in place of abstractions such as "weight" and "transfer function".
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] A neuron is filled and surrounded with water-containing ions, which carry electric charge.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The neuron is bound by an insulating cell membrane and can maintain a concentration of charged ions on either side that determines a capacitance *C*m.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The firing of a neuron involves the movement of ions into the cell, that occurs when neurotransmitters cause ion channels on the cell membrane to open.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] We describe this by a physical time-dependent current *I*(*t*).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] With this comes a change in voltage, or the electrical potential energy difference between the cell and its surroundings, which is observed to sometimes result in a voltage spike called an action potential which travels the length of the cell and triggers the release of further neurotransmitters.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The voltage, then, is the quantity of interest and is given by *V*m(*t*).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] If the input current is constant, most neurons emit after some time of adaptation or initial bursting a regular spike train.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The frequency of regular firing in response to a constant current *I* is described by the frequency-current relation, which corresponds to the transfer function $\varphi$ of artificial neural networks.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Similarly, for all spiking neuron models, the transfer function $\varphi$ can be calculated numerically (or analytically).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] All of the above deterministic models are point-neuron models because they do not consider the spatial structure of a neuron.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] However, the dendrite contributes to transforming input into output.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Point neuron models are valid description in three cases.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] (i) If input current is directly injected into the soma.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] (ii) If synaptic input arrives predominantly at or close to the soma (closeness is defined by a length scale $\lambda$ introduced below.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] (iii) If synapse arrives anywhere on the dendrite, but the dendrite is completely linear.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] In the last case, the cable acts as a linear filter; these linear filter properties can be included in the formulation of generalized integrate-and-fire models such as the spike response model.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The filter properties can be calculated from a cable equation.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Let us consider a cell membrane in the form of a cylindrical cable.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The position on the cable is denoted by x and the voltage across the cell membrane by V.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The cable is characterized by a longitudinal resistance $r_{l}$ per unit length and a membrane resistance $r_{m}$ .
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] We introduce a length scale $\lambda ^{2}={r_{m}}/{r_{l}}$ on the left side and time constant $\tau =c_{m}r_{m}$ on the right side.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The above cable equation is valid for a single cylindrical cable.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Linear cable theory describes the dendritic arbor of a neuron as a cylindrical structure undergoing a regular pattern of bifurcation, like branches in a tree.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] where *L* is the electrotonic length of the cylinder, which depends on its length, diameter, and resistance.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] A simple recursive algorithm scales linearly with the number of branches and can be used to calculate the effective conductance of the tree.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] where *A**D* = *πld* is the total surface area of the tree of total length *l*, and *L**D* is its total electrotonic length.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] where we can find the general correction factor *F**dga* experimentally by noting *G**D* = *G**md**A**D**F**dga*.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The linear cable model makes several simplifications to give closed analytic results, namely that the dendritic arbor must branch in diminishing pairs in a fixed pattern and that dendrites are linear.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] A compartmental model allows for any desired tree topology with arbitrary branches and lengths, as well as arbitrary nonlinearities.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] It is essentially a discretized computational implementation of nonlinear dendrites.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Each piece, or compartment, of a dendrite, is modeled by a straight cylinder of arbitrary length *l* and diameter *d* which connects with fixed resistance to any number of branching cylinders.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] We define the conductance ratio of the *i*th cylinder as *B**i* = *G**i* / *G*∞, where $G_{\infty }={\tfrac {\pi d^{3/2}}{2{\sqrt {R_{i}R_{m}}}}}$ and *R**i* is the resistance between the current compartment and the next.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] We can iterate these equations through the tree until we get the point where the dendrites connect to the cell body (soma), where the conductance ratio is *B*in,stem.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Importantly, static input is a very special case.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Moreover, dendrites are not always linear.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Compartmental models enable to include nonlinearities via ion channels positioned at arbitrary locations along the dendrites.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] For static inputs, it is sometimes possible to reduce the number of compartments (increase the computational speed) and yet retain the salient electrical characteristics.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The neurotransmitter-based energy detection scheme suggests that the neural tissue chemically executes a Radar-like detection procedure.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The detection scheme is similar to a radar-like "energy detection" because it includes signal squaring, temporal summation, and a threshold switch mechanism, just like the energy detector, but it also includes a unit that emphasizes stimulus edges and a variable memory length (variable memory).
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] According to this conjecture, the physiological equivalent of the energy test statistics is neurotransmitter concentration, and the firing rate corresponds to neurotransmitter current.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] The advantage of this interpretation is that it leads to a unit-consistent explanation which allows for bridge between electrophysiological measurements, biochemical measurements, and psychophysical results.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Stimulus edge emphasizing and signal transduction is performed by neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Temporal accumulation of neurotransmitters is performed by glial cells.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Short-term neurotransmitter accumulation is likely to occur also in some types of neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Logical switching is executed by glial cells, and it results from exceeding a threshold level of neurotransmitter concentration.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] This threshold crossing is also accompanied by a change in neurotransmitter leak rate.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Physical all-or-non movement switching is due to muscle cells and results from exceeding a certain neurotransmitter concentration threshold on muscle surroundings.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] Note that although the electrophysiological signals in Fig.6 are often similar to the functional signal (signal power/neurotransmitter concentration / muscle force), there are some stages in which the electrical observation differs from the functional purpose of the corresponding step.
[src:neural-simulation/leaky-integrate-and-fire-p02] In particular, Nossenson et al. suggested that glia threshold crossing has a completely different functional operation compared to the radiated electrophysiological signal and that the latter might only be a side effect of glia break.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Neural network simulators are software applications that are used to simulate the behavior of artificial or biological neural networks.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] They focus on one or a limited number of specific types of neural networks.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] They are typically stand-alone and not intended to produce general neural networks that can be integrated in other software.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Simulators usually have some form of built-in visualization to monitor the training process.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Some simulators also visualize the physical structure of the neural network.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Historically, the most common type of neural network software was intended for researching neural network structures and algorithms.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] The primary purpose of this type of software is, through simulation, to gain a better understanding of the behavior and the properties of neural networks.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Today in the study of artificial neural networks, simulators have largely been replaced by more general component based development environments as research platforms.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Commonly used artificial neural network simulators include the Stuttgart Neural Network Simulator (SNNS), and Emergent.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] In the study of biological neural networks however, simulation software is still the only available approach.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] In such simulators the physical biological and chemical properties of neural tissue, as well as the electromagnetic impulses between the neurons are studied.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Commonly used biological network simulators include Neuron, GENESIS, NEST and Brian.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Unlike the research simulators, data analysis simulators are intended for practical applications of artificial neural networks.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Their primary focus is on data mining and forecasting.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Data analysis simulators usually have some form of preprocessing capabilities.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Unlike the more general development environments, data analysis simulators use a relatively simple static neural network that can be configured.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] A majority of the data analysis simulators on the market use backpropagating networks or self-organizing maps as their core.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] The advantage of this type of software is that it is relatively easy to use.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Neural Designer is one example of a data analysis simulator.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] When the Parallel Distributed Processing volumes were released in 1986–87, they provided some relatively simple software.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] The original PDP software did not require any programming skills, which led to its adoption by a wide variety of researchers in diverse fields.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] The original PDP software was developed into a more powerful package called PDP++, which in turn has become an even more powerful platform called Emergent.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] With each development, the software has become more powerful, but also more daunting for use by beginners.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] In 1997, the tLearn software was released to accompany a book.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] In 2011, the Basic Prop simulator was released.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Basic Prop is a self-contained application, distributed as a platform neutral JAR file, that provides much of the same simple functionality as tLearn.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Development environments for neural networks differ from the software described above primarily on two accounts – they can be used to develop custom types of neural networks and they support deployment of the neural network outside the environment.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] In some cases they have advanced preprocessing, analysis and visualization capabilities.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] A more modern type of development environments that are currently favored in both industrial and scientific use are based on a component based paradigm.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] The neural network is constructed by connecting adaptive filter components in a pipe filter flow.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] This allows for greater flexibility as custom networks can be built as well as custom components used by the network.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] In many cases this allows a combination of adaptive and non-adaptive components to work together.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] The data flow is controlled by a control system which is exchangeable as well as the adaptation algorithms.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] The other important feature is deployment capabilities.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] With the advent of component-based frameworks such as .NET and Java, component based development environments are capable of deploying the developed neural network to these frameworks as inheritable components.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] In addition some software can also deploy these components to several platforms, such as embedded systems.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Component based development environments include: Peltarion Synapse, NeuroDimension NeuroSolutions, Scientific Software Neuro Laboratory, and the LIONsolver integrated software.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Free open source component based environments include Encog and Neuroph.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] A disadvantage of component-based development environments is that they are more complex than simulators.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] They require more learning to fully operate and are more complicated to develop.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] The majority implementations of neural networks available are however custom implementations in various programming languages and on various platforms.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Basic types of neural networks are simple to implement directly.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] There are also many programming libraries that contain neural network functionality and that can be used in custom implementations (such as TensorFlow, Theano, etc., typically providing bindings to languages such as Python, C++, Java).
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] In order for neural network models to be shared by different applications, a common language is necessary.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] The Predictive Model Markup Language (PMML) has been proposed to address this need.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] PMML is an XML-based language which provides a way for applications to define and share neural network models (and other data mining models) between PMML compliant applications.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] PMML provides applications a vendor-independent method of defining models so that proprietary issues and incompatibilities are no longer a barrier to the exchange of models between applications.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] It allows users to develop models within one vendor's application, and use other vendors' applications to visualize, analyze, evaluate or otherwise use the models.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] Previously, this was very difficult, but with PMML, the exchange of models between compliant applications is now straightforward.
[src:neural-simulation/neural-network-software] A range of products are being offered to produce and consume PMML.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Neuron models individual neurons via the use of sections that are automatically subdivided into individual compartments, instead of requiring the user to manually create compartments.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The primary scripting language is hoc but a Python interface is also available.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Programs can be written interactively in a shell, or loaded from a file.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Neuron supports parallelization via the MPI protocol.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Neuron is capable of handling diffusion-reaction models, and integrating diffusion functions into models of synapses and cellular networks.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Parallelization is possible via internal multithreaded routines, for use on multi-core computers.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The properties of the membrane channels of the neuron are simulated using compiled mechanisms written using the NMODL language or by compiled routines operating on internal data structures that are set up with Channel Builder.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Along with the analogous software platform GENESIS, Neuron is the basis for instruction in computational neuroscience in many courses and laboratories around the world.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Neuron features a graphical user interface (GUI), for use by individuals with minimal programming experience.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The GUI comes equipped with a builder for single and multiple compartment cells, networks, network cells, channels and linear electric circuits.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Single and multiple compartment cells differ in that multiple compartment cells features several "sections", each with potentially distinct parameters for dimensions and kinetics.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Tutorials are available on the Neuron website, including for getting basic models out of the cell, channel and network builders.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] With these builders, the user can form the basis of all simulations and models.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Cell Builder allows the user to generate and modify stick figure cell structures.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] These sections form the basis of functionally distinct areas of the neuron.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The user can define functionally distinct groups of sections.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Sections branching from one another can be labeled "dendrites," while another, single section that projects from the same central one can be labeled as the "axon." The user can define parameters along which certain values are variable as a function across a section.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] For instance, path length along a subset can be defined as a domain, the functions along which can then be defined later.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The user can select either individual sections, or groups and set precise parameters for length, diameter, area and length for that group or section.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Any of these values can be set as a function of length or some other parameter of the corresponding section.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The user can set the number of functional segments in a section, which is a strategy for spatial resolution.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The higher the number of segments, the more precisely Neuron can handle a function in a section.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Segments are the points where point process managers can be associated.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Users can define kinetic and electro-physiological functions across both subsets and sections.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Neuron comes equipped with a probabilistic model of Hodgkin-Huxley Model giant squid axon kinetics, as well as a function to model passive leak channel kinetics.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Both of these functions, and the features they describe, can be added to the membrane of the constructed cell.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Values for leak rate, sodium conductance and potassium conductance can be set for modeling these kinetics can be set as functions over a parameterized domain.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Channels become available for implementation in a cell membrane.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The user can generate both voltage- and ligand-gated channel models.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Channel Builder supports local point channels, generally used for single, large channels whose function is to be modeled, and general channels whose density across the cell can be defined.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Maximum conductance, reversal potential, ligand sensitivity, ion permeability, as well as precise dynamics of transitional states using activation and inactivation variables, and including differential conductance, can be defined.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Neuron allows for the generation of mixed models, populated with both artificial cells and neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Artificial cells essentially function as point processes, implemented into the network.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Artificial cells require only a point process, with defined parameters.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The user can create the structure and dynamics of network cells.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The user can create synapses, using simulated synapse point processes as archetypes.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Parameters on these point processes can be manipulated to simulate both inhibitory and excitatory responses.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Synapses can be placed on specific segments of the constructed cell, wherein, again, they will behave as point processes, except that they are sensitive to the activity of a pre-synaptic element.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The user creates the basic grid of network cells, taking previously completed network cells as archetypes.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Connections can be defined between source cells and target synapses on other cells.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The cell containing the target synapse becomes the post-synaptic element, whereas the source cells function as pre-synaptic elements.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Weights can be added to define strength of activation of a synapse by the pre-synaptic cell.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] A plot option can be activated to open a graph of spikes across time for individual neurons.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Neuron comes equipped with a slew of simulation tools.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Most notably, it includes several "point processes," which are simple functions at a particular segment of a cell.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Point processes include simulations of voltage, patch, single electrode and current clamps, as well as several simulated synapses.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Synapse point processes are distinct for their ability to model stimulation intensities that vary non-linearly across time.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] These can be placed on any segment of any section of a built cell, individual or network, and their precise values, including amplitude and duration of stimulation, delay time of activation in a run and time decay parameters (for synapses), can be defined from the point process manager module.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] When implemented into a network as synapses, point process parameters are defined in the synapse builder for a particular network cell.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Graphs describing voltage, conductance, and current axes over time can be used to describe changes in electrical state at the location of any segment on the cell.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] Neuron allows for graphs of change at both individual points over time, and across an entire section through time.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] All point processes, including those standing for cells or synapses of artificial neurons, and all graphs reflect the duration.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] This example creates a simple cell, with a single compartment soma and a multi compartment axon.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] It has the dynamics of the cell membrane simulated using Hodgkin-Huxley squid axon kinetics.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The simulator stimulates the cell and runs for 50 ms.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] A plot can be generated showing the voltage traces starting from the soma and the distal end of the axon.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The action potential at the end of the axon arrives slightly later than it appears in the soma at the point of stimulation.
[src:neural-simulation/neuron-software] The plot is membrane voltage versus time.
